article.headline: Texas blows out third straight opponent at home
article.linkText: Texas jumps to 15-0 lead, routs intrastate rival TCU
article.story:
AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- After a 2-2 start prompted a whole lot of
questions, Texas (No. 21 ESPN/USA Today, No. 23 AP) finally found what it was looking for Tuesday night in an 86-54 win over TCU.

	   Shooting, rebounding, defense and attitude all finally came
together for Texas in the Longhorns' third straight blowout win at
home.

	   ''Everything we've been lacking, I think we showed signs of
being capable tonight,'' Texas coach Jody Conradt said. ''We showed
something we hadn't before in terms of character and determination
and fight.

	   ''We still have to prove that we can win on the road.''

	   The victory over TCU (3-4) opened a four-game home stand for
Texas, which has struggled badly in two losses away from the Frank
Erwin Center. The Longhorns have won their three home games by an
average score of 91-38.

	   The Longhorns easily overmatched McNeese State and Southwest
Texas at home, and expected a stiffer test from the Horned Frogs.

	   Texas responded by winning the rebounding battle 40-31, forcing
20 turnovers and going 21-of-24 from the line.

	   Reserve Alisha Sare provided the scoring spark with 17 points,
14 in the first half. Heather Schreiber added 14 points, Stacy
Stephens 12 and Coco Reed 10 for the Longhorns (3-2).

	   ''That's my role on the team, to shoot the ball and open things
up for everyone else,'' Sare said.

	   The Longhorns took a 15-0 lead by turning eight TCU turnovers in
the first six minutes into 13 points. TCU got off just two shots in
that stretch.

	   ''We were very good defensively early,'' Conradt said. ''That
set the tone.''

	   The Horned Frogs cut the deficit to 23-14 with 7:31 left in the
half. Sare then scored nine of Texas' next 11 points, including a
steal and fastbreak layup and a 3-pointer that pushed the lead to
34-19.

	   Sare's 3-pointer with 4.3 seconds left in the half made it
44-26.

	   ''When you see her hit the first one, the second and third get
easier to her,'' said TCU coach Jeff Mittie.

	   Texas Christian, which hit 22 of 24 free throws, cut the lead to
48-36 early in the second half before Schreiber scored seven
straight in a 15-0 Texas run that pushed the lead to 63-36 with
10:13 to play.

	   Sandora Irvin and Ashley Browning scored nine points apiece for
TCU.

	   The Longhorns returned four of five starters from last year's
squad that made the round of 16 in the NCAA Tournament, only to be
humbled by losses at Brigham Young and New Mexico.

	   Schreiber said Texas is determined to turn things around during
this home stand, which includes a game Dec. 21 with No. 4
Tennessee.

	   ''We definitely didn't want to have a losing record,'' Schreiber
said. ''We wanted to come out and play well in this game.''
